<subSubSection id="686D16BD4D62974E3D8004DF37054355" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="DE3DC4F889B0AB8192DBFD2AFB0F442F" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9F7990C38EAE6007EF63E17209DF0059" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
Sexual dimorphism is distinct in 
<taxonomicName id="CE1D4483E5EC5BAF6ED00286A9582620" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Platythomisus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platythomisus" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Platythomisus</taxonomicName>
. Females can be easily distinguished from most other thomisids by their extraordinary large size [up to 20 mm in length in some specimens of the type species 
<taxonomicName id="D9EC02987381C13A6FE485AF922A79BB" genus="P." lsidName="P. octomaculatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="octomaculatus">P. octomaculatus</taxonomicName>
(C. L. Koch, 1845)] with strikingly contrasting color patterns on the carapace and opisthosoma. Typically, the epigyne has sclerotized margins and a conspicuous epigynal atrium; spermathecae longer than wide, well-sclerotized, and not divided into compartments. The male is much smaller than female (1:3 or more). Palp with VTA, ITA and RTA; tegulum flat, disk-shaped; tegular ridge present; embolus slender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
